{"cursor":"31204","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Enthalpy' is a measure of the total energy of a thermodynamic system. It\nincludes the internal energy, which is the energy required to create a system,\nand the amount of energy required to make room for it by displacing its\nenvironment and establishing its volume and pressure.\n\nEnthalpy is a thermodynamic potential. It is a state function and an extensive\nquantity. The unit of measurement for enthalpy in the International System of\nUnits (SI) is the joule, but other historical, conventional units are still in\nuse, such as the British thermal unit and the calorie.\n\nThe enthalpy is the preferred expression of system energy changes in many\nchemical, biological, and physical measurements, because it simplifies certain\ndescriptions of energy transfer. This is because a change in enthalpy takes\naccount of energy transferred to the environment through the expansion of the\nsystem under study.\n\nThe total enthalpy, H, of a system cannot be measured directly. Thus, change in\nenthalpy, ÎH, is a more useful quantity than its absolute value. The change ÎH\nis positive in endothermic reactions, and negative in heat-releasing exothermic\nprocesses. ÎH of a system is equal to the sum of non-mechanical work done on it\nand the heat supplied to it.\n\nFor processes under constant pressure, ÎH is equal to the change in the internal\nenergy of the system, plus the work that the system has done on its\nsurroundings. G.J. Van Wylen and R.E. Sonntag (1985), Fundamentals of\nClassical Thermodynamics, Section 5.5 (3rd edition), John Wiley & Sons Inc. New\nYork, NY. ISBN 0-471-82933-1 This means that the change in enthalpy under\nsuch conditions is the heat absorbed (or released) by a chemical reaction.\nEnthalpies for chemical substances at constant pressure assume standard state:\nmost commonly 1 bar pressure. Standard state does not, strictly speaking,\nspecify a temperature (see standard state), but expressions for enthalpy\ngenerally reference the standard heat of formation at 25 Â°C.\n","linknr":508,"url":"Specific_enthalpy","recorded":1362375093,"links":64,"instances":["thermodynamics","thermodynamics","physics","chemical_engineering","unit","systems","data_table","systems_theory","physics","chemistry","biochemistry"],"pdf":[],"categories":["State functions","Enthalpy|","Energy (physics)","Physical quantities"],"headings":["Origins","Formal definition","Other expressions","Enthalpy versus internal energy","Relationship to heat","Applications","Diagrams","Some basic applications","See also","Notes","References","Bibliography","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Carnot_heat_engine_2.svg/220px-Carnot_heat_engine_2.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/5/4/354c808b3ac7ff5bd75faa26bcc36220.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/9/e/b9ece18c950afbfa6b0fdbfa4ff731d3.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/e/7/de71b72c4f62f20d117414dd2f33ca25.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/d/9/8d9c307cb7f3c4a32822a51922d1ceaa.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/f/7/af7e8a85df47250ffab736b7a8807488.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/a/e/2aede3b55c027fe4392429d6474ec397.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/4/c/c4ca4238a0b923820dcc509a6f75849b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/8/8/888fa252e9cde41ef196d5154cd7219c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/2/0/5206560a306a2e085a437fd258eb57ce.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/f/5/1f58273c4161e57f62a95804c2ae961a.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/7/e/17eb927e31859ce116f5c64cbcc30d75.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/4/c/c4ca4238a0b923820dcc509a6f75849b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/8/8/888fa252e9cde41ef196d5154cd7219c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/2/0/5206560a306a2e085a437fd258eb57ce.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/f/7/af7e8a85df47250ffab736b7a8807488.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/1/5/8153e779d69fe6c35dc2bc4dfb0f2a11.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/7/5/5758e3126f